text: hi everyone
Anthony Fantana here intranets busiest
music nerd and it's time for a review of
the new Anamanaguchi LP endless fantasy
Anamanaguchi is a New York electronic
music outfit who is pretty well known
for combining rock instrumentation with
bright bright super bright 8-bit style
synthesizers and percussion it's the
sound that they've been molding since
those thousands to incorporate lots and
lots of melody super distorted guitars
pretty heavy drums taking musical cues
from video game soundtracks like super
r-type or numerous Mega Man games now
there's a plethora of different video
game musics out there and on amana Gucci
definitely does not take a ton of
influence from some of the more quirky
dark or even dramatic sounds to come out
of video game music
instead the music that automata Gucci
creates seems like it would be best set
to visuals of epic space battles
futuristic buildings colorful armored
lasers and hover cars reaching speeds of
100 miles per hour now the band's latest
LP endless fantasy also captures these
vibes but does it while stretching out
the band's stylistic basis meaning they
take their 8-bit sound and they just try
out more genres with it while primarily
the band was known for fusing rock
instrumentation with 8-bit sense and
percussion like I said earlier now on
endless fantasy the band is trying their
hand at Japanese pop electro pop a
little bit of house music now some of
the genre hopping that the band does on
endless fantasy is is very very much
needed because this is a pretty long
stretch of an album with 22 tracks
spanning 76 minutes in a way it's almost
as if the band is sort of making up for
lost time because it has been a while
since their last full-length LP if you
don't count the soundtrack music that
they did for the Scott Pilgrim video
game with so many tracks on this album
that feel very very similar emotionally
and sonically I can't help but feel like
even though I do enjoy endless fantasy
to an extent the album is somewhat
bogged down there are highlights on this
album for sure very well written
highlights and well produced
highlights but maybe they don't stick
out as well as they possibly could one
of the songs that dropped before the
selfie meow which I absolutely loved
when I first heard it and still do
loving the pumping bassline on this
track the silly meow sounds coming
through the song to the anthemic
synthesizes lead melodies on this track
that rush very colorfully as the chorus
soars meeny-meeny-meeny this song really
hits that sweet spot that Anamanaguchi
is great at hitting which combines very
awesome and anthemic and well written
melodies with just outright absurdity
while the band does have this real
talent for writing instrumental rock
tunes it just feels like they don't want
to take themselves too seriously and
just kind of keep things fun now while
some people may hate the inclusion of
this track on this album I will defend
for sure the song prom night it is an
electro-pop tune with a very
radio-friendly vocal beat and hook and
while I do think the lyrics on this
track are kind of cheesy the hook the
chorus is freakin killer and I actually
think if the band comes through with the
right music video for this track it
could kind of be their crossover hit I
dig the song in the basement because it
does bring a little bit of variation
with some breezier lighter instrumental
verses with some very clear guitar
strumming going on in there the songs
snow angels and planets stick out to me
because they are incredibly pretty slow
jams I'm loving how the band can just
take the tempo turn it down and make
something that is as pretty to listen to
as a very starry night sky is to look
into and some of the harder hitting
tracks like Veridian Genesis which is
pretty exciting with it's very sudden
tempo change in how a sort of blasts off
in a very speedy way however other
tracks on here just feel too similar in
style whether it's to other songs on
this album or previous material from
Anamanaguchi like the song SPF 420 feels
like the band grabbed one of their
previous singles airbrushed drove it to
a Chop Shop and then use parts from it
for this song and oddly enough one half
of the lead melody from the song pastel
flag sounds just like Nellie's dilemma
and tracks like a Keira or spaced wax
America while I do welcome all Weezer
and anime references I don't see what
these tracks bring to the album
others don't already and songs like
endless fantasy as well as Japan air
while automatic gucci is trying out
house music and a little bit of Japanese
pop on these tracks I don't see what
Anamanaguchi brings to the genres other
than an 8-bit aesthetic because I'm not
really in love with these tracks for
their Tunes or their structure I mean I
consider myself to be a pretty patient
listener for sure I have loved albums
that are much longer than this one I
just feel like their insistence on going
for this one sonic vibe on many of these
tracks drowns out some of this album's
hidden potential because even when a
song or a melody on this LP may be
particularly good it doesn't really
stick out because so many of the songs
on this LP there's not a lot of sonic
diversity for sure they're solid tracks
on this LP that I could enjoy singularly
but as I listen to this album as a whole
the experience is kind of like getting
belly sick off of a giant bag of candy
that I was pretty convinced once I
started eating it I could finish at
their worst on the cell P the tracks are
decent at their best they're great
they're fantastic do give this thing a
listen if you're looking for something
very melodic incredibly produced fun and
this feeling may last longer for you
than it did for me exciting I'm feeling
a strong 6 - Ally 7 on this thing if
you've given it a listen what did you
